Sucker for Stickers!
 
Have you been waiting for some fresh fruit-sticker fashion lewks? I know, I know... and I appreciate your patience ;p 

Well... here you go my Flower Girl Tribe: ​two NYC besties walk their pups sporting sticker ruffles, patchwork flares and belts. Once again, I had too much fun peelin-'n'playin with the little PLU fruit stickers that came on my Sumo Citrus® shipment. Folding a sticker to make the little pup coat was by far my fave detail. In case you don't know about this cult-favorite fruit, Sumo Citrus® is actually a type of Mandarin created in Japan and currently cultivated (very carefully, as its super delicate) in California. It's probably one of my fave fruits because it's clean to eat and easy to peel but still super juicy. Also, it jolts me up with the boost of Vitamin C I crave in winter and especially during postpartum.

#SumoCitrusPartner Need a mental break right now? Yeah, me too! 

Sit back, relax, make yourself comfy and watch how I dice and peel Sumo Citrus® to make some citrus couture. Thinly sliced peels, delicately bent for contour, create the pleated skirt of our lovely lady on the right. 

An orange sun hat (made from the fruit’s distinctive Top-Knot ™) completes the look. Delicately cut fruit slices comprise the more  structural skirt of our girl on the left. Just like the flowers I use, Sumo Citrus® has an ephemeral quality. 

Like any fruit, once peeled, its structure changes. Once Sumo Citrus® hits grocery shelves, it is also there only for a brief moment. I go to my Whole Foods in Brooklyn ( two blocks away luckily ) to stock up when the season is upon us... but so does everyone else. So, I’m bringing extra reusable bags to haul my goodies. You can find your closest Sumo Citrus® grocer on their website: www.sumocitrus.com.

This is 37 ! 🙃🎈 

What started off as a chaotic day (to say the least) juggling the kiddos and managing emotions (paired with unleashed toddler claws), ended as a beautiful one, celebrating life as a family of four. 

By divine intervention, we managed to make it out to dinner. A fellow diner with her own toddler who watched us sit down offered, seemingly unprompted, “you guys are doing great!” 

I’m not sure if she was reacting to us reposition chairs while Mike balanced a bottle under his chin to feed Izzy and I desperately pulled out Water Wow books for Parker, or she just saw the circles under our eyes and soulless expressions on our faces, but it made all the difference. Thanks, random woman.

We returned home to eat chocolate olive oil cake (infused with Ladurée Earl Grey tea!) that Mike whipped up this afternoon while all three girls slept … (also a birthday miracle). 

So, here’s to a great year ahead and days that can turn around.

Q&A WITH MEREDITH WING, THE ARTIST BEHIND @MOOMOOI 

🤍 when did you start your instagram account, @moomooi? what inspired you to start it and how did you choose your handle?

I started my account around 2013 and chose my handle because "moo" was a nickname from college. "mooi" sounded a little silly and like the french "moi" so i added it to the end, never thinking I’d have to explain it - haha! I started sharing artwork shortly thereafter, and the handle became associated with the art... it kept getting more and more too late to change it so I just stuck with it as a fun and whimsical moniker of sorts. It’s random, but it works and was easy to trademark! 

🤍 what was your first “big break”? did you feel like recognition was a gradual process or do you feel like it happened overnight?

Town & Country did a piece on my work around 2014 that went viral. that was a pretty big deal because t&c is such a major publication that I respect. up until that point my work was purely personal and for fun, so having editorial coverage of that caliber felt very legitimizing. shortly after that, soho house asked me to go to coachella with them and draw portraits at their estate. I was still in architecture school at columbia university during this time and beginning to feel like I did not want to practice architecture, so these two "breaks" gave me the confidence to found meredith wing design llc and make "moomooi" a full time career in 2015. I haven't looked back since.

“Coachella Artist in Residence” ✨ 

CONFESSION: 

Imposter Syndrome has always been an issue for me ; often feeling like I don’t deserve to do the work I do, or am not talented enough to collaborate with the brands I help. I get worried about disappointing people or not being good enough because my art training isn’t formal (I developed graphic design skills in architecture school but don’t have an MFA). 

This feeling was especially bad when MooMooi was starting out in 2015, but I had to overcome it quickly when @sohohouse invited me to the iconic Coachella music festival. They asked me to be their “Artist in Residence” and draw celebrity portraits on their estate and, in that moment, I knew I just had to OWN IT: myself, my skills, my services.

Despite being in the middle of pin-ups during my final year of a grueling, three year, full-time Masters of Architecture program at Columbia University, I said YES. I had to. I was, coincidentally, starting to feel like the architecture practice wasn’t for me. I was just so happy drawing and “building” on a micro scale and sharing what I did with my virtual and in-person audiences… leaning into this feeling helped me grow.

“Should I go?” I asked my now-husband Mike.

“One hundred percent. GO.” he said. 

I knew the gig was a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity, so I closed my laptop and boarded the flight. Doing so, just going for it at Coachella, helped me to feel legitimate as an artist. In this way, have @billievanthof and @sohohouse to thank for my career. 

The rest is history. 

Once in the desert, I was quickly whisked away to a dreamy estate with the likes of @rosiehw , @katyperry , @zoeisabellakravitz @rmdrk , brands like @coach , @greygoose , @shopbazaar etc.

I had so much fun playing, making art, socializing and meeting so many wonderful women who are still my  friends and peers (I see you @stefancypants @courtgazaleh). I actually never made it to any music (though I did manage to go to Neon Carnival 🫠) and I never looked back.

For so many reasons, my “PRIDE,” mural, completed in the heart of NYC on 5th Ave and 42nd, is my fave of all time.

A giant work stretching half a city block, “PRIDE,” was created for @andaz5th in 2018. Depicting a scene in front of the West Village’s Stonewall Inn, made famous for the 1969 gender riots, a rainbow-hued group of people in matching fruits and flowers decorate the walls. 

The subjects are fourteen-foot-tall figures dressed in everything from blueberries to poppies to mint and lemon. Some figures chat, two dads push a stroller, a woman runs errands, a mom and son grab ice cream, another couple walks a French bulldog. All pretty normal, everyday stuff for people who just wanna live happy lives…but in a way made more special for the colors and vibrancy it imparts.

9/11 + NYC

In memory of September 11, 2001, a tribute to the city I love and called home for the majority of my adult life : NYC. The best on earth. And to America, a resilient and diverse world leader forever a beautiful work-in-progress.

I will never forget that day, my first as a “Lower” (high school Sophomore) at Andover @phillipsacademy. By mid-morning, students and faculty alike were huddled around the campus TVs. When it became clear this was a terrorist attack, and not a rogue airplane accident (as it initially seemed), The Dean called an All School Meeting and classes were cancelled. Kids from NYC desperately called home only to be met by the sound of broken phone lines.

As then President @georgewbush was an alumnus along with his father, they thought our school was potentially an extra target. Everyone was sent home halfway through our first day of class. 

My now-husband, Mike, a freshman at Columbia University in NYC, watched the towers go down while standing on the roof of his dorm with his new classmates. They were 130+ blocks north of the Ground Zero.

Later that afternoon, he walked south with a backpack and flashlight, in what seemed like the pitch black of night, to see if anyone needed help.

Time passes, but we never forget.

Flower Pumpkin Toddler Tutorial !
 
This was SO easy, pretty, and fool-proof for a rainy weekend activity with a kid… Parker exclaimed “Mommy I’m having so much fun in your studio!”

MATERIALS

1) white pumpkin(s) - big mama and two babies make a cute set

2) pressed flowers (do them yourself for extra extra points or buy via Amazon for efficiency! linked in stories)

3) Mod Podge Glue/Sealer 16oz 

4) Brushes (bristle or foam but for me foam ones bubble thin mediums like water-based glue)

5) painters tarp

DIRECTIONS 

1) set down plastic painters tarp for sticky spills and lay down a towel for little ones to sit on

2) wipe off excess dirt from pumpkin and / or scrub with dish soap for clean surface - wipe and allow to dry 

3) apply think layer of Mod Podge medium under desired flower area 

4) press flower directly to gluey spot being mindful of readjusting too many times and risk rubbing off pressed flower dye 

5) use tweezers to avoid sticky hands if you want ! Be sure to fully press down petals / leaves so they’re flush to pumpkin surface 

6) arrange with candles for elegant seasonal vibez

4) allow to dry for minimum 20 minutes then apply another layer of Modge Podge 

5) leave overnight in ventilated room to fully dry

my heart is hurting 💙 

Last night I went to sleep sobbing, thinking of those sweet little kids going to bed in their pajamas and wet hair, cruelly and mercilessly losing their lives the next day. I’m trying to navigate how to show up on Instagram and share my art, personal life and connect with my community (which brings me joy) but at the same time not ignore atrocities going on in the world. 

Silence is dangerous, but having a voice implies knowing what to say and how to say it. @deepakchopra said some interesting words recently about community and creativity being a healer of hurt, and I think that’s true so I’m leaning into my relationships including my digital ones here with YOU. 

I think this is a moment for kindness and for savoring of our peace too. But that also feels complicated. How do we hold space for both joy and mourning? How do we communicate meaningfully with others in a culture of sound bites.

If you have any thoughts or advice, let me know here. 
I always want to come from a place of service in my own, albeit very niche way. 

I also know I’m not the only one navigating these things so at least we have that.

As some of you know, I am a half-Chinese-Catholic, half-Austrian-Jewish mama of two! 

I grew up north of Boston celebrating both Hanukkah and Christmas, so I am thrilled that Talbots has invited me to share my heritage with all of you this year through some magical imagery.  #TalbotsPartner

The tradition of Hanukkah has a special place in my family's holiday season. Each year, since I was a little girl, I have lit the menorah on the eight days of Hanukkah. We light these candles and say a prayer to commemorate the ancient Jewish miracle in which oil that should have only lasted one day was able to illuminate a holy menorah for eight days during an oppressive time. 

This year, I am honored to celebrate the "festival of lights" with my two little girls (first time for "Izzy"!) by giving them a little gift for each of the eight nights, as per tradition. 

More importantly, I am just looking forward to creating space to be together as a family. In addition to making traditional hanukkah latkes, we will also trim our Christmas tree, bake cookies, and write letters to Santa. 

All celebrations of life, love, and family are extra special to us this year in our new home. Talbots cashmere sweaters, silky skirts and ornaments complete the holiday package...
